{
  "doc_id": "28845",
  "text": "It is well accepted that a pronounced DC maturation status is important for the induction of efficient immune responses by DC immunotherapy [CITATION_1] . In our study, both DC preparations showed only marginal upregulation of the maturation marker CD83, which is a result from culture conditions using serum free medium [CITATION_2] . Gene expression analysis revealed that IL-4/TNF-DC have more immature DC characteristics. This was indicated by the higher expression of several genes envolved in phagocytosis such as Fc and complement receptors as well as genes envolved in epithelial adhesion structure formation including the genes for vinculin or the integrin αE chain. In contrast to this finding, IFN-DC showed a higher expression of several alternative DC maturation markers than IL-4/TNF-DC that are involved in antigen processing (DCLAMP [CITATION_3] ), migration to and localization in the lymph nodes (CCR7 [CITATION_4] , integrin α4 [CITATION_5] and decysin [CITATION_6] ) as well as survival (BCL2A1 [CITATION_7] ). Therefore, on molecular level, IFN-DC show the prerequisite to initiate an adaptive immune response in the lymph node [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Importantly, this capacity of IFN-DC could be demonstrated functionally by a higher migratory capacity of IFN-DC in vitro compared to IL-4/TNF-DC as shown by transwell experiments. This is also in line with [CITATION_10] , who had shown before that IFN-DC have a higher migratory potency than IL-4-DC not stimulated by TNF-α [CITATION_11] .",
